---- 03 Python Project: Game Development ----
-- Louis Radcliffe --

GitHub repository link: https://github.com/LouisRadcliffe572/rockborne-python-project.git

My game is Noughts and Crosses
Load Jupyter Notebook file or copy & paste script into chosen Python software

Run "def game()" script to define game function
Run "game()" to play the game

"Input a player name:" as prompted
"Input another player name:" as prompted
Script will randomly decide which player goes first: "__ will go first!"
"[first player], noughts or crosses? (o/x)" as prompted
Script will lowercase input and check it is either 'o' or 'x'
"[first player] is [noughts or crosses], [second player] is [crosses or noughts]."
Empty game board will be printed

"[first player], where would you like to play?" as prompted
    Input format requires two consecutive letters representing row and column
    For rows: t = top, m = middle, b = bottom
    For columns: l = left, m = middle, r = right
    e.g. 'tr' for top right, 'mm' for middle middle
    Script will lowercase input and check it is a recognised position
Updated board will be printed
"[second player], where would you like to play?" as prompted
    If position is already occupied, script will display an error message and prompt for a position again
Updated board will be printed

This process repeats until either a win condition has been met:
    Three of the same character across a row, column or diagonal
or the game is a draw:
    All positions are occupied without a win condition being met
"[winner] wins!" or "It's a draw! You'll have to play again!"
"Scores:"
"[first player]: [their score], [second player]: [their score]"
    This is printed after every game, with scores updated accordingly
    The order of names in the scores list remains consistent throughout following games
"Keep playing? (type 'exit' to stop playing)" as prompted
    If 'exit' is input, script will end
    If anything else is input, a new game will start with the same players and scores carried over
    The order of play alternates between games

If play continues:
    Resets appropriate variables and loops back to the start of the game process
    All following games will have "It is [appropriate starting player]'s turn to start."
        The message will use the correct apostrophe choice based on whether the player's name ends with an 's':
        e.g. "It is Louis' turn to start." or "It is Cam's turn to start."
        (it is a pet hate of mine when sites and automated responses get this wrong, so I wanted to make sure my game got it right)
If play does not continue:
    "Final Scores:"
    "[first player]: [their total score], [second player]: [their total score], Total games = [game count]"
    "[overallwinner] is the winner!"
    "Thank you for playing!"
    Script ends
